article.description:
The Indiana Fever spent the first half of
Thursday's game with the Portland Fire tying a turnover record.
article.headline: McCray tallies 30 to help Fever edge Fire
article.linkText: McCray, Catchings lead Fever over Fire
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The Indiana Fever spent the first half of
Thursday's game with the Portland Fire tying a turnover record.

	   They spent the second half challenging a WNBA scoring record.

	   Nikki McCray scored 20 of her 30 points in the second half, and
Tamika Catchings had 22 points, five assists and nine rebounds as
Indiana snapped a three-game losing streak with an 81-72 victory
over the Fire on Thursday night.

	   Olympia Scott-Richardson added 10 points and nine rebounds for
the Fever (5-5), who scored 59 second-half points, seven shy of the
record, to overcome an eight-point halftime deficit.

	   "We had a healthy talk at halftime,'' Fever coach Nell Fortner
said. "You've got to take it to the other team. Our defense really
dictates a lot of our offense; we got steals in the second half and
got layups. When that starts happening, your confidence builds
because that feels good.''

	   Catchings had just five points and five of Indiana's 14
turnovers in the first half, tying a record for a Portland
opponent. But the Fever opened the second half with a 22-8 run to
reclaim the lead for good.

	   "Fourteen turnovers was the difference in the game (at the
half),'' Fortner said. "We had to cut down on that and give
ourselves opportunities for shots.''

	   The Fever kept the turnover total to five and started attacking
the basket, resulting in 30 second-half free-throw attempts.

	   "Everybody stepped up in the second half so they couldn't key
on any one player,'' Catchings said. "And even though they were
denying me, they were holding me. They kept fouling me so we kept
going to the free throw line.''

	   Said Fortner: "She's hard to guard one-on-one. She got to the
free throw line, and that's where she can really make a living.''

	   Catchings was 10-of-12 from the line in the second half.
Portland was in the penalty for the last 12 minutes of the game.

	   LaQuanda Barksdale scored a career-high 13 points and DeMya
Walker had 12 for Portland (4-6). Ukari Figgs added 11 points for
the Fire, who had won four of their last five and were looking to
reach .500 for the first time since last July 24.

	   Neither scored over the game's opening 2:19 and Portland didn't
score until nearly four minutes had gone by.

	   The Fire closed the first half by outscoring Indiana 19-7 over
the final 8:19. Portland finished the half shooting 35.5 percent
after starting 1-of-10.

	   For the third consecutive game, Portland center Sylvia Crawley
was a non-factor, scoring just four points. In her last four games,
Crawley has scored a total of 15 points on 6-of-29 shooting.
